TY  - GEN
TI  - Adolescents and Social Media: Longitudinal Links Between Types of Use, Problematic Use and Internalizing Symptoms
AU  - Marie-Pier Gingras
AU  - M. Brendgen
AU  - M. Beauchamp
AU  - J. Séguin
AU  - R. Tremblay
AU  - S. Côté
AU  - C. Herba
PY  - 2023
UR  - https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/e3fe2247ff78f6a8407cd42cb7e7836a64fae90b
DO  - 10.1007/s10802-023-01084-7
JO  - Research on Child and Adolescent Psychopathology
AB  - Longitudinal cross-lagged panel study of 257 adolescents (ages 13–14). Problematic social media use predicted later anxiety symptoms (β = .16); active use predicted higher anxiety only in adolescents low in extraversion. Social media use preceded anxiety — not the reverse — offering stronger directional evidence than cross-sectional designs. **Methodology:** Cross-lagged panel model (CLPM), two-wave longitudinal with self-report diaries and questionnaires. **Limitations:** Small sample; single two-year window; limited to self-report.
