TY  - GEN
TI  - The longitudinal effect of social media use on adolescent mental health in the UK: findings from the UK Longitudinal Household Study.
AU  - R. Plackett
AU  - J. Sheringham
AU  - J. Dykxhoorn
PY  - 2022
UR  - https://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/10166817/1/Plackett_43213-741563-1-LE.pdf
DO  - 10.1016/S0140-6736(22)02281-4
JO  - The Lancet
AB  - Large UK Longitudinal Household Study (N = 3,228, ages 10–15, 2009–2019). In adjusted longitudinal models, time spent on social media at ages 12–13 did NOT predict poorer mental health at ages 14–15. Self-esteem mediated the relationship only in unadjusted models. A rare null result from a high-quality, well-powered cohort — directly challenges the assumed causal link. **Methodology:** Multilevel linear regression; path analysis with structural equation modelling; two-wave follow-up. **Limitations:** Mental health measured only by broad SDQ difficulty score; social media use measured on a coarse 5-point scale.
ER  - 
TY  - GEN
TI  - Whether and how will using social media induce social anxiety? The correlational and causal evidence from Chinese society
AU  - Feng Yang
AU  - Minya Li
AU  - Yan Han
PY  - 2023
UR  - https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2023.1217415/pdf?isPublishedV2=False
DO  - 10.3389/fpsyg.2023.1217415
JO  - Frontiers in Psychology
AB  - Two-study design (N = 470 survey + N = 180 lab experiment) testing causality. Survey confirmed upward social comparison → lowered self-esteem → social anxiety pathway. Lab experiment randomly assigned participants to social media content vs. nature documentaries, finding significantly higher social anxiety in the social media group. The lab component is among the cleaner experimental demonstrations of causality for the social comparison mechanism. **Methodology:** Correlational survey + controlled lab experiment with random assignment. **Limitations:** University students only (not minors); Chinese sample may limit generalization; lab content may not reflect naturalistic use.
