TY  - GEN
TI  - Association of Screen Time and Depression in Adolescence.
AU  - E. Boers
AU  - M. H. Afzali
AU  - N. Newton
AU  - P. Conrod
PY  - 2019
UR  - https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapediatrics/articlepdf/2737909/jamapediatrics_boers_2019_oi_190041.pdf
DO  - 10.1001/jamapediatrics.2019.1759
JO  - JAMA pediatrics
AB  - Four-year longitudinal study of 3,826 adolescents (mean age 12.7) from 31 Montreal schools. Each additional hour of social media use was associated with increased depressive symptoms both between- and within-person. Crucially, associations were better explained by upward social comparison and reinforcing spirals (social media → lower self-esteem → more use) than by displacement of exercise. **Methodology:** Multilevel within-person and between-person models; secondary analysis of a 4-year RCT cohort. **Limitations:** Depression (not anxiety specifically) was the primary outcome; self-report measures; correlation direction not definitively established.
