TI  - Cyberbullying Victimization and Mental Health Symptoms Among Children and Adolescents: A Meta-Analysis of Longitudinal Studies
AU  - Jungup Lee
AU  - Hyekyung Choo
AU  - Yijing Zhang
AU  - H. S. Cheung
AU  - Qiyang Zhang
AU  - Rebecca P. Ang
PY  - 2025
UR  - https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/a4d392770ca07d2f886edd90cca55dff2f0100fb
DO  - 10.1177/15248380241313051
JO  - Trauma, Violence, & Abuse
AB  - Meta-analysis of 27 longitudinal studies (N = 13,497, ages 8–19) on cyberbullying victimization and mental health. Found a consistently positive but weak longitudinal association. Effect was larger in older adolescents, males, and more recent publications. The longitudinal design across studies provides the strongest aggregate evidence for a directional (not merely correlational) cyberbullying → mental health link. **Methodology:** Systematic review and meta-analysis of longitudinal studies (2010–2021). **Limitations:** Wide variation in follow-up intervals and outcome measures; weak effect sizes suggest other confounders.
