TY  - GEN
TI  - Cyberbullying Perpetration and Victimization in Youth: A Meta-Analysis of Longitudinal Studies
AU  - L. Marciano
AU  - P. Schulz
AU  - A. Camerini
PY  - 2020
UR  - https://academic.oup.com/jcmc/article-pdf/25/2/163/33146622/zmz031.pdf
DO  - 10.1093/jcmc/zmz031
JO  - J. Comput. Mediat. Commun.
AB  - Meta-analysis of 56 longitudinal studies on cyberbullying perpetration and victimization. Found that cybervictimization constitutes a risk factor for internalizing problems (depression, anxiety) over time, while pre-existing depression and anxiety also predicted subsequent cybervictimization — a bidirectional relationship. **Methodology:** 40 separate meta-analyses; moderator analyses by study design, sample, and quality. **Limitations:** High heterogeneity across studies; reverse causation confirmed (bidirectionality).
