TI  - Longitudinal Associations between Cybervictimization and Mental Health Among US Adolescents
AU  - Chad A. Rose
AU  - B. Tynes
PY  - 2015
UR  - https://europepmc.org/articles/pmc6956839?pdf=render
DO  - 10.1016/j.jadohealth.2015.05.002
JO  - Journal of Adolescent Health
AB  - Three-wave longitudinal study of 559 U.S. adolescents (grades 6–12) over three years. Cybervictimization at time 1 predicted anxiety at time 2, and anxiety at time 1 predicted cybervictimization at time 2 — a reciprocal relationship confirmed across multiple waves. **Methodology:** Cross-lagged longitudinal panel; self-report. **Limitations:** Self-report only; no randomization; sample from limited geographic area.
