TI  - Longitudinal Associations Between Cyberbullying Involvement and Adolescent Mental Health.
AU  - Amanda Fahy
AU  - S. Stansfeld
AU  - M. Smuk
AU  - N. Smith
AU  - S. Cummins
AU  - C. Clark
PY  - 2016
UR  - https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/1cb141d9e43c38786f6870796281d92b25c262ba
DO  - 10.1016/j.jadohealth.2016.06.006
JO  - Journal of Adolescent Health
AB  - Longitudinal study of 2,480 adolescents (ages 12–13) in East London, one-year follow-up. Cybervictims were 1.52× more likely to report social anxiety and 1.44× more likely to report depression at follow-up, controlling for baseline mental health. One of the larger individual longitudinal studies with clear adjustment for prior symptoms. **Methodology:** Prospective cohort; logistic regression adjusted for confounders including baseline mental health. **Limitations:** One-year window; self-report; no experimental manipulation.
