TI  - Cross‐sectional and longitudinal associations of screen time with adolescent depression and anxiety
AU  - Sophie H Li
AU  - P. Batterham
AU  - Alexis E. Whitton
AU  - Kate Maston
AU  - Asaduzzaman Khan
AU  - Helen Christensen
AU  - A. Werner‐Seidler
PY  - 2025
UR  - https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdfdirect/10.1111/bjc.12547
DO  - 10.1111/bjc.12547
JO  - British Journal of Clinical Psychology
AB  - Large nationally representative cross-cohort analysis of U.S. adolescents (N = 8.2 million, ages 13–18, 1976–2017). Found that iGen adolescents in the 2010s spent less time in face-to-face interaction as digital media use increased, and loneliness rose sharply after 2011. Adolescents combining low face-to-face interaction with high social media use were loneliest. **Methodology:** Nationally representative time-series data; cohort-level analysis. **Limitations:** Correlational; does not establish that social media causally displaces interaction at the individual level (paradoxically, individual-level analysis shows positive correlation between both).
