TI  - Longitudinal Links Between Adolescent Social Anxiety and Depressive Symptoms: Testing the Mediational Effects of Cybervictimization
AU  - N. van Zalk
AU  - M. V. van Zalk
PY  - 2018
UR  - https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007%2Fs10578-018-0829-1.pdf
DO  - 10.1007/s10578-018-0829-1
JO  - Child Psychiatry and Human Development
AB  - Longitudinal study (N = 501 early adolescents) examining whether cybervictimization mediates the path from social anxiety to depression over time. Found that social anxiety predicted later cybervictimization, which in turn predicted depressive symptoms — suggesting pre-existing anxiety may increase vulnerability to online victimization. **Methodology:** Cross-lagged longitudinal mediation model. **Limitations:** Social anxiety may pre-date cybervictimization (directionality complex); adolescent sample from one country.
