TI  - Social Media Use, Friendship Quality, and the Moderating Role of Anxiety in Adolescents with Autism Spectrum Disorder
AU  - Gerrit I. van Schalkwyk
AU  - Carla E Marin
AU  - Mayra Ortiz
AU  - Max J Rolison
AU  - Zheala Qayyum
AU  - J. McPartland
AU  - Eli R. Lebowitz
AU  - F. Volkmar
AU  - W. Silverman
PY  - 2017
UR  - https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6688174
DO  - 10.1007/s10803-017-3201-6
JO  - Journal of Autism and Developmental Disorders
AB  - Cross-sectional study of 44 adolescents with ASD and 56 clinical controls. In adolescents with ASD, social media use was positively associated with friendship quality, but this was moderated by anxiety level — only lower-anxiety ASD adolescents benefited. Relevant as a contrast case: social media can support friendship quality for some populations (those for whom face-to-face interaction is particularly difficult). **Methodology:** Cross-sectional; small clinical sample. **Limitations:** Very small sample (N=100); cross-sectional; ASD population may not generalize.
